accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Donated to the Rockefeller Archive Center by Alexandra (Sascha) Rockefeller.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Rodman Clark Rockefeller (May 2, 1932 â€“ May 14, 2000) was an American businessman, philanthropist, and philanthropic administrator. He was the eldest son of former Nelson Aldrich Rockefeller and Mary Todhunter Clark.

Rodman Rockefeller attended Dartmouth College, and conducted graduated studies at Columbia for which he earned a master's degree in business administration. He served as a trustees for a variety of institutions including but not limited to: the America's Society, the Institute of International Education, the Thomas Jefferson Memorial Foundation, the Museum of Modern Art, the New York Blood Center and the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.
He also served as a trustee of Rockefeller Financial Services, which manages the Rockefeller family's office (known as "Room 5600") and Rockefeller and Company.

Rockefeller also served as co-chairman of the Mexico-United States Business Committee, an organization focused on economic, political, and cultural relations that was significantly involved in advocating for what ultimately became the North American Free Trade Association (NAFTA).

Rodman Rockefeller also had a long association with the International Basic Economy Corporation for which he served as vice president (1968 to 1972), chief executive (1972 to 1980), and chairman of its successor organization IBEC, Inc. (1980-1985).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection primarily consists of personal and professional correspondence, board records and supporting materials, trip files, speeches, remarks, and records of personal and political contributions. Rodman Rockefeller's diverse interests and activities are well represented including documentation of his involvement with the International Basic Economy Corporation (IBEC), Pocantico Development Associates, Arbor Acres Farm, the Institute of International Education (IIE), Dartmouth College, and the Museum of Modern Art.

There is also a small selection of research materials from Kenneth Durr (Series VI) pertaining to his work on the history of IBEC, including IBEC annual reports and a compliation of chronological correspondence from Mr. Rockefeller.
